# LAP CLI

Search and download API specs from the LAP registry. The registry contains 231+ APIs already compiled into LAP format -- just search and download, no compilation needed.

## Command Resolution

Always use `npx` -- it works without any global install:

```bash
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh <command>
```

All examples below use `npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh`. If the user has `lapsh` installed globally, you may use that instead.

---

## How to get an API spec

Two commands. Nothing else.

```bash
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh search <query>
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh get <name> -o <name>.lap
```

Example:
```bash
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh search plaid
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh get plaid -o plaid.lap
```

The `<name>` is the first column from search results. The `.lap` file is the complete API spec -- endpoints, parameters, auth, schemas. Read it and start coding.

**Important: do NOT do any of these:**
- Do NOT download the raw OpenAPI/Swagger YAML -- the `.lap` file replaces it
- Do NOT compile or convert anything -- the registry returns ready-to-use `.lap` files
- Do NOT download both `.lap` and `.lean.lap` unless the user asks -- one file is enough
- Do NOT fetch from any URL other than the LAP registry -- `get` handles everything

---

## Install a skill (optional)

If the user wants a persistent skill installed for Cursor:

```bash
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh skill-install <name> --target cursor
```

This installs to `~/.cursor/rules/<name>/` with a `.mdc` file. **Always pass `--target cursor`** -- without it the skill installs to the wrong directory.

---

## Compile a local spec (advanced)

If the user has a local OpenAPI/GraphQL/AsyncAPI spec file instead of using the registry:

```bash
npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh compile <spec-file> -o output.lap
```

---

## Troubleshooting

| Problem | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| `npx` hangs or fails | Run `npx -y @lap-platform/lapsh` (the `-y` skips confirmation) |
| No results from search | Try broader terms (e.g., "payment" instead of "stripe charges") |
| `get` returns empty | The API name must match the first column from search results exactly |
